{
  "texts": [
    "Microlensing variability depends on the relative size of micro-caustics on the source plane with respect to the emitting source.",
    "A typical value for this size is R E that is ∝ M/M 1/2 (Eq.",
    "(7)), where M is the microlens mass.",
    "The masses for a population of microlenses are, in principle, free to vary in the broad range roughly from small star clusters (or even intermediate mass black holes) to sub-stellar objects like planets and moons.",
    "In the latter case, one can speak of 'nano-lensing', 20 which is still relevant for quasars as long as there is a wavelength to observe in which their emitting region is accordingly small."
  ]
}